2) Evaluation of the two CDs against that neutral-but-CD-loving stance:
- With the Beatles (Beatles, 1963) is an early Beatles album that showcases tight vocal harmonies, concise melodic songwriting by Lennon–McCartney, and a mix of original compositions and well-chosen covers (examples on the album include "All My Loving" and their energetic take on "Roll Over Beethoven" and "Please Mister Postman"). It is widely regarded as historically important within the British Invasion and classic-pop/rock canon, broadly accessible to general listeners, and represents a varied listening experience across short, well-crafted tracks.
- For Those About to Rock (We Salute You) (AC/DC, 1981) is a hard rock/arena-rock album built around punchy, riff-driven songs and anthemic production (title track and other cuts emphasize heavy guitar, driving rhythm, and stadium-scale choruses). It is excellent for fans of hard-driving rock and live-sounding anthems but is stylistically narrower and louder compared with the melodic and harmonic variety on a Beatles album.
3) Reasoned choice and justification:
Because my only stated preference is an enjoyment of listening to CDs (with no stated taste for a particular subgenre), I prioritize a disc that offers broad appeal, melodic variety, and historical listening value. With the Beatles fits that criterion better: its combination of memorable melodies, vocal harmonies, concise songcraft, and place in popular-music history makes it an especially rewarding listen for a general CD enthusiast who wants both immediate musical enjoyment and a sense of significance. In contrast, For Those About to Rock is a stronger pick for listeners specifically seeking hard, stadium-style rock and powerful guitar riffs; its stylistic focus makes it somewhat less suited as the default choice for someone whose only stated preference is simply enjoying CDs in general. Therefore I select With the Beatles for its wider accessibility, melodic and harmonic richness, and cultural significance, and I reject For Those About to Rock because its heavier, arena-oriented sound is more niche and less varied for a broadly oriented CD listener.

