herent sequencing and collector packaging” aligns with my desire for a cohesive, start‑to‑finish album flow and collectible presentation/liner notes.\n- Taken together, CD 2 satisfies the majority of my stated requirements: tonal focus (warm mids), preserved dynamics, rhythmic/punchy mixes, intact album content, and collector packaging. These are the decisive factors for me.\nWhy CD 1 is rejected:\n- Although CD 1 has some positive technical traits (minimally compressed, detail‑forward mastering that “preserves headroom and vocal nuance”), its format and sequencing conflict with explicit dislikes. It is an “energetic greatest‑hits” collection with “momentum‑driven sequencing” that makes tracks “single‑ready and remix‑friendly,” and it “spotlight[s] a single front‑of‑mix vocal.” My self‑introduction specifically calls out a dislike for greatest‑hits/single‑oriented compilations and multi‑era or radio‑polished hits collections because they often use variable masters or edited single versions that break album flow.\n- CD 1’s emphasis on funk/clean guitar/punchy synths and a single front‑of‑mix vocal also suggests a singles‑focused presentation rather than the layered, riff‑driven, album‑flow hard‑rock I prioritize. Even though its mastering is detail‑forward and minimally compressed, the compilation/singles orientation and potential for variable mastering/sequencing make it a poor fit for my stated collector‑grade, album‑flow preferences.\nConclusion: CD 2 best aligns with my documented priorities for warm mid‑forward tonality, preserved dynamics and punch, thick guitar/drum mixes, intact full‑length tracks and solos, coherent sequencing, and collector packaging — all of which outweigh the limited points of agreement offered by CD 1.'. \n\n However, upon actually listening to these two CDs, you discovered that you don't like the CD that you initially chose ('The Very Best of Prince'). Instead, you prefer the CD that you did not choose before ('The Ultimate Sin Remaster